\pard\plain \tx720\li720\fi-720\sb360\ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs28\b1\i0 J.}{\f0\fs28\b0\i0 \tab }{\f1\fs28\b1\i0 Abram Had the Covenant Reconfirmed by God: Aroused Faith\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 the Steps to a Fresh, Stirring Experience with God, 17:1\endash 27}
\par\pard\plain \sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 (17:1\endash 27) }{\f1\fs24\b1\i0 Introduction}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 : Abram was desperate. He had been wanting a son ever since his marriage to Sara, and they most likely had been married for over fifty years. Thus Abram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s longing\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 his hopes and dreams\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 to have a son had been gnawing at him for over fifty years. But Sara had been unable to bear children. In desperation, when Abram was an old man, Sara had suggested that Abram take her maid, Hagar, and try to bear a son through her before it was too late. This Abram did, and Ishmael was born. Abram\u8217\'92s dreams for a son were finally realized in Ishmael. Did Abram ever expect to have another son, a son other than Ishmael? Not likely, for he was now ninety-nine years old, and Sara was eighty-nine, both well beyond childbearing years. Abram was well aware of this fact; verse 17 tells us this. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Apparently Abram had felt that Ishmael was the son promised by God, that God was going to fulfill His promises through Ishmael. Abram loved Ishmael dearly. Note verse 18, where Abram cried out for God to remember and bless Ishmael. Ishmael was thirteen years old, and because of Abram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s life-long desire for a son, he no doubt loved Ishmael more deeply than the average father. The bond between them was probably closer than the bond between most fathers and sons. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Apparently Abram had become comfortable and settled in life, somewhat complacent and lethargic, slumbering and slacking off. Abram just accepted reality: he was too old to bear any more children, and Ishmael was the only child he had. Thus he felt Ishmael was bound to be the son promised by God.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \fi360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 But as this passage so clearly reveals, this was not God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s plan. Ishmael was not the promised seed, not the son promised to Abram. Thus Abram\u8217\'92s faith needed to be aroused once again. Abram needed God to arouse\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 stir, quicken, awaken\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 his faith to look beyond Ishmael \u8230\'85}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \bullet \tab beyond the present}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \bullet \tab beyond the physical}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \bullet \tab beyond the possible}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Abram needed to be renewed, to look at the impossible and to believe in the miraculous power and works of God. Note how this is exactly what we need. When a believer becomes comfortable\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 at ease, complacent, and lethargic\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 in life, he needs to be aroused by God. He needs a fresh, stirring experience with God similar to Abram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s experience. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 This is the subject of this important passage: }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 Abram Had the Covenant (Promises) Reconfirmed by God: Aroused Faith\hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2 the Steps to a Fresh, Stirring Experience with God}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 , 17:1\endash 27.}
\par\pard\plain \tx720\li720\fi-360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 1.\tab Step 1: receiving a fresh revelation from God: God is the Almighty God (v. 1).}
\par\pard\plain \tx720\li720\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 2.\tab Step 2: making a new commitment to walk before God and to live a blameless, perfect life (vv. 1\endash 2).}
\par\pard\plain \tx720\li720\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 3.\tab Step 3: humbling oneself before God and listening to God (vv. 3\endash 5).}
\par\pard\plain \tx720\li720\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 4.\tab Step 4: hearing and believing God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s covenant or promises (vv. 6\endash 8).}
\par\pard\plain \tx720\li720\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 5.\tab Step 5: keeping the covenant and sharing in the ritual of the covenant: keeping its meaning always in one\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s mind (vv. 9\endash 14).}
\par\pard\plain \tx720\li720\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 6.\tab Step 6: changing the relationship to one\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s family (vv. 15\endash 18).}
\par\pard\plain \tx720\li720\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 7.\tab Step 7: accepting the will and purpose of God (vv. 19\endash 21).}
\par\pard\plain \tx720\li720\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 8.\tab Step 8: making a public decision and obeying God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s instructions, His Word (vv. 22\endash 27).}
\par\plain \f3\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f3\fs24\b0\i0 \{\\Scrv_fn= Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). \\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/posbkjv01ge2?ref=Bible.Ge17.1-27&off=6183&ctx=cumcised+with+him.%0a%0a~J.+Abram+Had+the+Cov"}{\fldrslt\f4\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis (Chapters 12\endash 50)\\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  (Vol. II, p. 79). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.\\end_Scrv_fn\}}
\par\plain \f3\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f3\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Abram was ninety-nine years old and Sara eighty-nine. It was physically impossible for them to conceive a child. Thus what Abram needed was to see God as }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 El Shaddai}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 , the Almighty God, the God who possessed all might and power, the God who could do anything. Almighty God could quicken the bodies of Abram and Sara and make them fertile and cause a son to be born to them. Abram needed to believe this promise; he needed to believe the impossible. Therefore, God revealed Himself as the Almighty God, the God of all power, the God who could fulfill His promise and who could meet the needs of Abram and his dear wife. (See }{\f5\fs20\b0\i0\scaps Deeper Study}{\f5\fs20\b0\i0  # 1}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 , }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 Almighty God}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 Ge. 17:1 for more discussion.)}
\par\pard\plain \li720\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs24\b1\i0 Thought 1}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 . God is the Almighty God; He possesses all might and all power. He can do all things; in fact, there is nothing that God cannot do.}
\par\pard\plain \li720\fi360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Thus when we face difficult, impossible circumstances, we should seek God, seek the power and promises of God. We should seek a fresh revelation from God, to see God as the Almighty God, as the God who can do all things.}
\par\plain {\f3\fs24\b0\i0 \{\\Scrv_fn= Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). \\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/posbkjv01ge2?ref=Bible.Ge17.1&off=406&ctx=childbearing+years:+~Abram+was+ninety-nin"}{\fldrslt\f4\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis (Chapters 12\endash 50)\\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  (Vol. II, pp. 79\endash 80). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.\\end_Scrv_fn\}}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs24\b1\i0 Walk, Spiritual\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 Believer, Life}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 : How can we arouse our faith, have a fresh, stirring experience with God? Step two is to make a new commitment to walk before God and to live a perfect or blameless life. The believer\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s life is not a static, complacent life. When God gives us a fresh revelation\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 some new insight or knowledge\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 He expects us to act, to put the new knowledge to use, and to grow thereby. This was true of Abram. God gave Abram a fresh revelation of Himself as the Almighty God, but God also told Abram to recommit his life and to do so more diligently than ever before. God charged Abram to make two commitments:}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 a. He was }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 to walk before God}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 : this means to live step by step in the presence of God; to live moment by moment in fellowship with God; to live in an unbroken consciousness of God; to be always aware of God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s presence, power, and security. Three pictures are painted by this descriptive phrase.}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab To walk before God means that we live before Him in a spirit of devotion, worship, fellowship and service.}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab To walk before God means that we do not walk behind Him nor ahead of Him. But we walk before Him, conscious that He can see us and that He has the power to look after and care for us.}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab To walk before God means that we are aware of His power to see and know all, aware that He will judge us for all we do}
\par\plain \f3\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f3\fs24\b0\i0 \{\\Scrv_fn= Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). \\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/posbkjv01ge2?ref=Bible.Ge17.1-2&off=5074&ctx=19:15).%0a%0a2+(17:1%E2%80%932)+~Walk%2c+Spiritual%E2%80%94Beli"}{\fldrslt\f4\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis (Chapters 12\endash 50)\\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  (Vol. II, pp. 80\endash 81). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.\\end_Scrv_fn\}}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \li720\fi360\qj\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He was }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 to be perfect or blameless}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  (tamim). This means just what the Hebrew word says: to be sound, complete, without any lack or failure whatsoever; it means to be blameless, without blemish. Scripture is }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 not teaching sinless perfection}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 , for no person has or ever will live a }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 sinless}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  and perfect life, no person other than Jesus Christ our Lord. But Scripture is teaching }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 holiness}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 , that Abram and all other believers are to walk before God diligently seeking to live perfect, blameless lives. We are \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \bullet \tab to live holy lives before Him}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \bullet \tab to develop a heart that is single-minded, set upon God first and foremost throughout all of life}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \bullet \tab to live lives that are wholly devoted to the Lord}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \bullet \tab to be conformed to the image of Christ}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \bullet \tab to please God with all our hearts}
\par\pard\plain \li720\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs24\b1\i0 Thought 1}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 . We live in days of immorality, lawlessness, and violence; and tragically we make excuse after excuse for our loose living. We do our own thing, live like we want, and try to excuse our sinful behavior by blaming society, environment, circumstances, or the weakness of human nature. But note the words of Arthur W. Pink as he explains the kind of life we are to live before God:\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). \\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/posbkjv01ge2?ref=Bible.Ge17.1-2&off=7309&ctx=ed%E2%80%9D+(1+Jn.+2:6).%0ab.+~He+was+to+be+perfect"}{\fldrslt\f4\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis (Chapters 12\endash 50)\\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  (Vol. II, p. 81). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.\\end_Scrv_fn\}}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 How can we arouse our faith, have a fresh, stirring experience with God? Step three is to humble ourselves before God and to listen to God, to His Word, to what He has to say to us. No doubt, Abram immediately fell on his face at the first appearance of God. The brightness of God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s glory would strike any person to the ground. The point is this: Abram humbled himself before God; he got as low as he could to show reverence for God, that he was ready to listen and to receive whatever message God had for him. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 God said two things to Abram:}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \fi360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 a. God reminded Abram that it was he who had been chosen to receive the covenant of the promised seed. He and he alone, not someone else, had been chosen to be the father of many nations.}
\par\pard\plain \li720\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs24\b1\i0 Thought 1}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 . The stress is upon God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s call, the appointment of Abram to be God\u8217\'92s servant. When God calls us\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 any of us\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 to serve Him, we must humble ourselves before Him and listen to His call.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 b. God changed Abram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s name to Abraham (v. 5). The meaning of Abram is }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 high father}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 ; the meaning of Abraham is }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 the father of a multitude}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 . This experience with God was to be a turning point in Abram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s life: }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 the promised seed}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  was soon to be born through Sarai. Thus God gave Abram a new name to remind him of this experience with God: God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s great call and covenant, of God\u8217\'92s great assurance to fulfill His promise.}
\par\pard\plain \li720\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch \f1\fs24\b1\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b1\i0 Thought 1}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 . God has given the believer the very name of His own dear Son, }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 Christian}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  (Acts 11:26; 26:28; 1 Pe. 4:16). The great need of the hour is for believers to humble themselves before God and remember the great name He has given them, the name of }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 Christian}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 . The name should remind us \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \bullet \tab of our conversion experience}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \bullet \tab of other deep experiences with God}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \bullet \tab of God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s great call to us, the great task He has given each of us to do}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \bullet \tab of God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s promises (covenant) of His assurance to fulfill the promises made to us}
\par\plain \f3\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f3\fs24\b0\i0 \{\\Scrv_fn= Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). \\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/posbkjv01ge2?ref=Bible.Ge17.3-5&off=21&ctx=+(17:3%E2%80%935)+Humility:+~How+can+we+arouse+ou"}{\fldrslt\f4\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis (Chapters 12\endash 50)\\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  (Vol. II, p. 82). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.\\end_Scrv_fn\}}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 There was the promise of }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 the promised seed}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  (vv. 6\endash 7). Abraham was to be very fruitful. His descendants were to include nations of people, and some were to be very prominent, holding the highest office possible, that of king. Remember, Abraham was the father of \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \bullet \tab the Arabs through Ishmael}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \bullet \tab the Jews through Isaac}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \bullet \tab the nations born of a third wife, Keturah (see Ge. 25:1\endash 4)}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \bullet \tab the believers of the world: Scripture says that we are the spiritual children of Abraham (Ga. 3:7\endash 9; see Ro. 4:11\endash 12)}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Now, note what else God says: the promised seed is an everlasting covenant established by Him (v. 7). What does this mean? It means that Abraham will have descendants upon earth as long as the earth stands.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \fi360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 But note another fact as well: God established the promised seed as an everlasting covenant for a reason: that He might be the God of the promised seed, be their God forever. God wants a personal relationship with Abraham\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s descendants; He wants a people with whom He can fellowship and pour out His mercy and grace, a people who will worship, serve, and live for Him eternally.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 This is very significant, for it tells us exactly with whom God established the everlasting covenant. The everlasting covenant applies to Abraham and all those who follow in the steps of Abraham. Who are they? Believers. All persons who walk upon earth believing God just as Abraham believed God; all persons who follow after God just like Abraham did. The point is this:}
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab God gave Abraham the promise of the promised seed, of many nations and descendants.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \tx1080\li1080\fi-360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8658\'3F\tab But God also gave Abraham a very special promise: that He would establish the covenant of the promised seed }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 forever}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 . There would always be those who would do just what Abraham did: believe God and follow diligently after God. And God would be the God of these descendants forever. Note that this is the promise of eternal life\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 an everlasting covenant\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 to those who truly follow after God as Abraham did.\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). \\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/posbkjv01ge2?ref=Bible.Ge17.6-8&off=393&ctx=ore+discussion.)%0aa.+~There+was+the+promis"}{\fldrslt\f4\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis (Chapters 12\endash 50)\\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}}{\f3\fs24\b0\i0  (Vol. II, pp. 82\endash 83). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.\\end_Scrv_fn\}}
